	abstract = {Plant responses to global changes in carbon dioxide ({CO}2), nitrogen, and water availability are critical to future atmospheric {CO}2 concentrations, hydrology; and hence climate. Our understanding of those responses is incomplete, however. Multiple-resource manipulation experiments and empirical observations have revealed a diversity of responses, as well as some consistent patterns. But vegetation models-currently dominated by complex numerical simulation models-have yet to achieve a consensus among their predicted responses, let alone offer a coherent explanation of the observed ones. Here the propose an alternative approach based on relatively simple optimization models ({OMs}). We highlight the results of three recent forest {OMs}, which together explain a remarkable range of observed forest responses to altered resource availability. We conclude that {OMs} now offer a simple yet powerful approach to predicting the responses of forests-and, potentially; other plant types-to global change. We recommend ways in which {OMs} could be developed further in this direction.},
